  "derivation_layer": {
    "source_latex": "% BEGIN TZP DERIVATION LAYER\n\\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}\n\\paragraph{Primary Equation.}\n\\begin{equation}\nK_{\\mathrm{NL}}\n=\n\\frac{\\left\\lVert \\nabla^{2}\\varphi\\right\\rVert}\n{\\left\\lVert \\nabla\\varphi\\right\\rVert^{2}} .\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}\nLet $\\varphi$ be a scalar field on the Trawinistic manifold.  \nThe first-order variation of the field is measured by the gradient:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\nabla\\varphi .\n\\end{equation}\n\nThe second-order curvature or bending of the field is measured by:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\nabla^2\\varphi .\n\\end{equation}\n\nA dimensionless measure of non-linearity should compare second-order deformation against the square of first-order variation. Therefore define:\n\n\\begin{equation}\nK_{\\mathrm{NL}}\n=\n\\frac{\\text{second-order field deformation}}\n{\\text{first-order field variation squared}} .\n\\end{equation}\n\nSubstituting the appropriate differential norms gives:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\boxed{\nK_{\\mathrm{NL}}\n=\n\\frac{\\left\\lVert \\nabla^{2}\\varphi\\right\\rVert}\n{\\left\\lVert \\nabla\\varphi\\right\\rVert^{2}} .\n}\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Interpretation.}\n$K_{\\mathrm{NL}}$ measures how sharply a field bends relative to its local rate of change. Large values indicate strong nonlinear behavior near the TZP.\n% END TZP DERIVATION LAYER"
  },
